<doc id="340198" wikidata="Q1778098" url="?curid=340198" title="Pointwise convergence">
<text>In mathematics, pointwise convergence is one of various senses in which a sequence of functions can converge to a particular function. It is weaker than uniform convergence, to which it is often compared.

==Definition==

Suppose that formula_1 is a set and formula_2 is a topological space, such as the real or complex numbers or a metric space, for example. A sequence of functions formula_3 all having the same domain formula_1 and codomain formula_2 is said to converge pointwise to a given function formula_6 often written as
formula_7
if (and only if) the limit of the sequence formula_8 evaluated at each point formula_9 in the domain of formula_10 is equal to formula_11, written as
formula_12
The function formula_10 is said to be the pointwise limit function of the formula_14

The definition easily generalizes from sequences to nets formula_15. We say formula_16 converges pointwise to formula_10, written as
formula_18
if (and only if) formula_11 is the unique accumulation point of the net formula_20 evaluated at each point formula_9 in the domain of formula_10, written as
formula_23

Sometimes, authors use the term bounded pointwise convergence when there is a constant formula_24 such that formula_25 .

==Properties==

This concept is often contrasted with uniform convergence. To say that
formula_26
means that
formula_27
where formula_28 is the common domain of formula_10 and formula_30, and formula_31 stands for the supremum. That is a stronger statement than the assertion of pointwise convergence: every uniformly convergent sequence is pointwise convergent, to the same limiting function, but some pointwise convergent sequences are not uniformly convergent. For example, if formula_32 is a sequence of functions defined by formula_33 then formula_34 pointwise on the interval formula_35 but not uniformly.

The pointwise limit of a sequence of continuous functions may be a discontinuous function, but only if the convergence is not uniform. For example,
formula_36
takes the value formula_37 when formula_9 is an integer and formula_39 when formula_9 is not an integer, and so is discontinuous at every integer.

The values of the functions formula_30 need not be real numbers, but may be in any topological space, in order that the concept of pointwise convergence make sense. Uniform convergence, on the other hand, does not make sense for functions taking values in topological spaces generally, but makes sense for functions taking values in metric spaces, and, more generally, in uniform spaces.

==Topology==

Let formula_42 denote the set of all functions from some given set formula_1 into some topological space formula_44
As described in the article on characterizations of the category of topological spaces, if certain conditions are met then it is possible to define a unique topology on a set in terms of which nets do and do not converge. 
The definition of pointwise convergence meets these conditions and so it induces a topology, called the , on the set formula_42 of all functions of the form formula_46 
A net in formula_42 converges in this topology if and only if it converges pointwise. 

The topology of pointwise convergence is the same as convergence in the product topology on the space formula_48 where formula_1 is the domain and formula_2 is the codomain. 
Explicitly, if formula_51 is a set of functions from some set formula_1 into some topological space formula_2 then the topology of pointwise convergence on formula_54 is equal to the subspace topology that it inherits from the product space formula_55 when formula_54 is identified as a subset of this Cartesian product via the canonical inclusion map formula_57 defined by formula_58 

If the codomain formula_2 is compact, then by Tychonoff&#x27;s theorem, the space formula_42 is also compact.

==Almost everywhere convergence==

In measure theory, one talks about &quot;almost everywhere convergence&quot; of a sequence of measurable functions defined on a measurable space. That means pointwise convergence almost everywhere, that is, on a subset of the domain whose complement has measure zero. Egorov&#x27;s theorem states that pointwise convergence almost everywhere on a set of finite measure implies uniform convergence on a slightly smaller set.

Almost everywhere pointwise convergence on the space of functions on a measure space does not define the structure of a topology on the space of measurable functions on a measure space (although it is a convergence structure). For in a topological space, when every subsequence of a sequence has itself a subsequence with the same subsequential limit, the sequence itself must converge to that limit. 

But consider the sequence of so-called &quot;galloping rectangles&quot; functions (also known as the typewriter sequence), which are defined using the floor function: let formula_61 and formula_62 mod formula_63 and let
formula_64

Then any subsequence of the sequence formula_65 has a sub-subsequence which itself converges almost everywhere to zero, for example, the subsequence of functions which do not vanish at formula_66 But at no point does the original sequence converge pointwise to zero. Hence, unlike convergence in measure and formula_67 convergence, pointwise convergence almost everywhere is not the convergence of any topology on the space of functions.

